In [1]:
# Author: Stephen Situ
# This project aims to create a tensorflow neural network model for multiclass-classification of animals. Given the data in 3 csv files,
# we union them, and then join them with a class csv file for the full dataframe. We also note that if we use the category as integers,
# we must start with 0 for the neural network. Using our baseline model for multiclass-classification, we get an accuracy 28%. After we 
# make various changes like changing neurons per layer, epochs, learning rate, and optimizer. We find that increasing learning rate and
# neurons per layer were the most effective for our final model. This final model gets 100% accuracy. 
# Then we plot loss/accuracy charts for our models, create confusion matrices, and look at the model visualizations on tensorboard
# original data here: 
# https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/uciml/zoo-animal-classification
# https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/agajorte/zoo-animals-extended-dataset

# Read 3 csv files, union them, then rename column
# Then subtract 1 from "Class-Index" column to make classification intergers start from 0 (need to do this for neural network)
df1 = pd.read_csv("zoo.csv")
df2 = pd.read_csv("zoo2.csv")
df3 = pd.read_csv("zoo3.csv")
df4 = pd.concat([df1,df2,df3])
df5 = df4.rename(columns={'class_type': 'Class_Index'})
df5["Class_Index"] = df5["Class_Index"] - 1
df5

# For Multi-Class classification with 7 categories, set last dense layer to 7 and activation function to "softmax"
# Also use SparseCategoricalCrossentropy() for loss function for integers
# Use Categorical Cross Entropy if data is one hot encoded
# default lr is 0.001
# start with 20 epochs 2 hidden layers with 4 neurons

In [15]:
# Create tensorflow multiclass-classification model
# Get 26% accuracy on first model
# Set random seed
tf.random.set_seed(45)

# Create the model
model_1 = tf.keras.Sequential([
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation="relu"),
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation="relu"),
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(7, activation="softmax") 
])

# Compile the model
model_1.compile(loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(),
                 optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(lr=0.001), 
                 metrics=["accuracy"])

# Fit the model
history_1 = model_1.fit(test_data_x_ten,
                       test_data_y_ten,
                       epochs=20)

# Create tensorflow multiclass-classification model
# Try using 2 100 neuron layers and get 88% accuracy
# Set random seed
tf.random.set_seed(45)

# Create the model
model_2 = tf.keras.Sequential([
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(100, activation="relu"),
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(100, activation="relu"),
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(7, activation="softmax") 
])

# Compile the model
model_2.compile(loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(),
                 optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(lr=0.001), 
                 metrics=["accuracy"])

# Fit the model
history_2 = model_2.fit(test_data_x_ten,
                       test_data_y_ten,
                       epochs=20)

# Create tensorflow multiclass-classification model
# try doubling the epochs, epochs = 40
# Get 26% accuracy
# Set random seed

# Create the model
model_3 = tf.keras.Sequential([
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation="relu"),
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation="relu"),
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(7, activation="softmax")
])

# Compile the model
model_3.compile(loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(),
                 optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(lr=0.001), 
                 metrics=["accuracy"])

# Fit the model
history_3 = model_3.fit(test_data_x_ten,
                       test_data_y_ten,
                       epochs=40)

# Create tensorflow multiclass-classification model
# Try learning rate of 0.01 and get 30% accuracy
# Set random seed
tf.random.set_seed(45)

# Create the model
model_4 = tf.keras.Sequential([
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation="relu"),
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation="relu"),
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(7, activation="softmax")
])

# Compile the model

                 optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(lr=0.01), 
                 metrics=["accuracy"])

# Fit the model
history_4 = model_4.fit(test_data_x_ten,
                       test_data_y_ten,
                       epochs=20)

# Create tensorflow multiclass-classification model
# Try using Stochastic Gradient Descent optimizer, get 26%
# Set random seed
tf.random.set_seed(45)

# Create the model
model_5 = tf.keras.Sequential([
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation="relu"),
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation="relu"),
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(7, activation="softmax") 
])

# Compile the model
model_5.compile(loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(),
                 optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.SGD(lr=0.001),

# Create tensorflow multiclass-classification model
# Try using learning rate callback to find optimal learning rate
# Set random seed
tf.random.set_seed(45)

# Create the model
model_6 = tf.keras.Sequential([
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation="relu"),
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation="relu"),
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(7, activation="softmax") 
])

# Compile the model
model_6.compile(loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(),
                 optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(lr=0.001), # ideal learning rate (same as default)
                 metrics=["accuracy"])

# Create a learning rate scheduler callback
lr_scheduler = tf.keras.callbacks.LearningRateScheduler(lambda epoch: 1e-4 * 10**(epoch/20)) # traverse a set of learning rate values starting from 1e-4, increasing by 10**(epoch/20) every epoch


# Fit the model
history_6 = model_6.fit(test_data_x_ten,
                       test_data_y_ten,
                       epochs=20,
                      callbacks=[lr_scheduler])

# Best model results were when we used 2 100 neurons layers and also increasing lr from 0.001 to 0.01
# We will try a combination
# Create tensorflow multiclass-classification model
# Try using 2 100 neuron layers with lr = 0.01, we get  accuracy close to 100% accuracy
# Set random seed
tf.random.set_seed(45)

# Create the model
model_7 = tf.keras.Sequential([
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(100, activation="relu"),
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(100, activation="relu"),
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(7, activation="softmax") # output shape is 39, activation is softmax
])

# Compile the model
model_7.compile(loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(),
                 optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(lr=0.01), # ideal learning rate (same as default)
                 metrics=["accuracy"])

# Fit the model
history_7 = model_7.fit(test_data_x_ten,
                       test_data_y_ten,
                       epochs=20, callbacks=[tensorboard])

# Plot the learning rate versus the loss
# Rule of thumb, optimal learning rate is 10x smaller than bottom of the curve
# In this case, bottom is 0.1, 10x smaller is 0.01
lrs = np.linspace(start=1e-4, stop=1e-1, num=20)
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
plt.semilogx(lrs, history_6.history["loss"]) # we want the x-axis (learning rate) to be log scale
plt.xlabel("Learning Rate")
plt.ylabel("Loss")
plt.title("Learning rate vs. loss");

In [95]:
# Make function for pretty confusion matrix
# Note: The following confusion matrix code is a remix of Scikit-Learn's 
# plot_confusion_matrix function - https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.metrics.plot_confusion_matrix.html
# and Made with ML's introductory notebook - https://github.com/GokuMohandas/MadeWithML/blob/main/notebooks/08_Neural_Networks.ipynb
import itertools
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

# Our function needs a different name to sklearn's plot_confusion_matrix
def make_confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred, classes=None, figsize=(10, 10), text_size=15): 
  """Makes a labelled confusion matrix comparing predictions and ground truth labels.

  If classes is passed, confusion matrix will be labelled, if not, integer class values
  will be used.

  Args:
    y_true: Array of truth labels (must be same shape as y_pred).
    y_pred: Array of predicted labels (must be same shape as y_true).
    classes: Array of class labels (e.g. string form). If `None`, integer labels are used.
    figsize: Size of output figure (default=(10, 10)).
    text_size: Size of output figure text (default=15).
  
  Returns:
    A labelled confusion matrix plot comparing y_true and y_pred.

  Example usage:
    make_confusion_matrix(y_true=test_labels, # ground truth test labels
                          y_pred=y_preds, # predicted labels
                          classes=class_names, # array of class label names
                          figsize=(15, 15),
                          text_size=10)
  """  
  # Create the confustion matrix
  cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
  cm_norm = cm.astype("float") / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis] # normalize it
  n_classes = cm.shape[0] # find the number of classes we're dealing with

  # Plot the figure and make it pretty
  fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=figsize)
  cax = ax.matshow(cm, cmap=plt.cm.Blues) # colors will represent how 'correct' a class is, darker == better
  fig.colorbar(cax)

  # Are there a list of classes?
  if classes:
    labels = classes
  else:
    labels = np.arange(cm.shape[0])
  
  # Label the axes
  ax.set(title="Confusion Matrix",
         xlabel="Predicted label",
         ylabel="True label",
         xticks=np.arange(n_classes), # create enough axis slots for each class
         yticks=np.arange(n_classes), 
         xticklabels=labels, # axes will labeled with class names (if they exist) or ints
         yticklabels=labels)
  
  # Make x-axis labels appear on bottom
  ax.xaxis.set_label_position("bottom")
  ax.xaxis.tick_bottom()

  # Set the threshold for different colors
  threshold = (cm.max() + cm.min()) / 2.

  # Plot the text on each cell
  for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
    plt.text(j, i, f"{cm[i, j]} ({cm_norm[i, j]*100:.1f}%)",
             horizontalalignment="center",
             color="white" if cm[i, j] > threshold else "black",
             size=text_size)
